@node "main" "ProNET-Control documentation"

                   ProNET-Control Version 1.0
                   ==========================


      © 2002 Dave Norris

      ProNET-Control is a front end for ProNET.
      It makes it possible to mount/dismount any devices
      on the client, by using only the mouse.


      @{" System Requirements " link "requirements"        0}
      @{" Installation        " link "installation"        0}
      @{" How it works        " link "works"        0}


      Tabs:
      @{" Startup   " link "safety"    0} - Info/prefs page
      @{" Server    " link "server"          0} - If this computer is to be the server
      @{" Client    " link "client"       0} - If this computer is to be the client
      @{" » Mount   " link "mount"      0} - Mount/dismount devices on the client
      @{" » Page    " link "page"      0} - Send guru type message to the server
      @{" » Talk    " link "talk"       0} - Chat between the client and server


      @{" Bugs etc. " link "bugs"    0} - Please tell me
      @{" Credits   " link "Credits"    0} - Where it's due 

@endnode


@node "requirements" "System requirements"


  System requirements
  ===================

  AWNPipe, which is used for the gui.

  AWNPipe uses ClassAct/ReAction, so OS 3.5 or above, or ClassAct installed.
  
  And of course, ProNET to do the work.

  If ProNET is not installed, ProNET-Control goes into a safe 'demo' mode,
  this is to give anyone trying it out an idea of how it operates.


  Tested under OS3.9, bb1, bb2,
  Using a 9 Metre serial cable between two A1200's, 030/40's.
  Entry in both .config files = serial serial.device 0 57600
@endnode


@node "installation" "Installation"


  Installation
  ============

  ProNET-Control can be put wherever you wish. So long as AWNPipe
  and ProNET are installed, it will work from anywhere.

@endnode


@node "works" "How it works"
                     

  How it works - Getting the list of devices from the server
  ==========================================================

  The ram: device is on all Amigas, so after the server has been started
  up, the command 'pronet-start guest ram 0 unique' is run from the
  client when the 'scan server' button is clicked. This mounts the servers
  'Ram Disk' on the client as '0Ram Disk'.

  @{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub} Pronet-start will fail if the server has not been started up
  first, it waits for a response from the server, which never arrives, so
  ProNET-Control is left hanging with a busy pointer. 
  This only applies when using a serial connection, with a parallel device
  it does not matter which is started up first.

  Next the command 'pronet-run 0 "info ram:scan"' is executed which gets
  a list of the devices on the server, in a file on the servers ram: device.

  This is copied to the client by 'copy guest:scan T:scan', followed by
  deleting the file on the server with 'pronet-run 0 "delete ram:scan"'.

  The servers ram: device is then dismounted from the client by executing
  'pronet-stop guest'.

  The file 'T:scan' then gets examined to extract the information that
  goes into the listbrowser on the client.


@endnode


@node "safety" "Safety, just in case"


  Startup
  =======

  The info window lets you know if the program has started up in 'demo'
  mode or not, depending on if the ProNET files have been found.
  With 'demo' on, it is safe to use any of the gadgets.

  The prefs gadgets let you snapshop the ProNET-Control window,
  and to start up iconfied.

@endnode


@node "server" "Server startup"


  Server
  ======

  The top listbrowser is for the possible connections the user can have
  with other machines. The list is loaded up from 'Devs:ProNET/.config'.

  The listbrowser below lists the connections the user has started up.
  If ProNET-Control is closed down with the connections still active,
  the connections will be shut down automatically.

@endnode


@node "client" "Client tabs"


  Client
  ======

  The client tab leads to the three tabs below.

      @{" Mount     " link "mount"      0} - Mount/dismount devices on the client
      @{" Page      " link "page"      0} - Send a guru type message to the server
      @{" Talk      " link "talk"       0} - Chat between the client and server
@endnode


@node "mount" "Mount or dismount devices on the client"


  Mount/Dismount
  ================

  The chooser gadget selects the unit number to scan the server on,
  the same unit number as the server.  The amount of unit numbers
  will be the same as the amount of connections the user has in the
  .config file.  If .config cannot be found, then the chooser gadget
  will number 0 to 2, to enable the user to use 'demo mode'.

  After clicking 'Scan server', the listbrowser loads up with a list of
  devices from the server (or the client if 'demo' mode is on).
  The 'Scan server' button will ghost if any devices are mounted.


  Listbrowser columns:
  ====================

  Status - displays 'Active' or 'Off ', depending on the device being
  mounted or unmounted.

  Local Name - gives you the 'hidden' device name that will be used
  to mount the device on the client.  This can be changed by the user.
  If the name is not changed by the user, then a number is appended
  to the name when it is mounted on the client.

  Remote Name - is the name of the device on the server, this is changed
  to the name in 'Local Name' when the device is mounted on the client.

  Volume Name - is the name of the device on the servers Workbench, the
  same name will appear on the Workbench if the device is mounted.
  If the same name already exists on the client, then the unit number
  is appended to the front of the name.

  Unique - displays the volume name that will appear on the clients Workbench
  if the 'Volume Name' already exists on the client.



  When a device is clicked, the 'Local Name' appears in the string gadget,
  this is to enable the user to change the name if they wish.

  To mount or dismount a device, simply double-click on the device.

  If ProNET-Control is closed down while any devices are still mounted,
  they will be dismounted automatically.



@endnode



@node "page" "Send a message to the server"


  Client/Page
  ===========

  After clicking 'Send message', anything you have entered in the
  string gadget will appear in a yellow guru box on the server.

  The chooser gadget selects the unit number to run pronet-page on,
  the same unit number as the server.

@endnode


@node "talk" "Chat with another computer"


  Client/Talk
  ==========

  Clicking the button on this page will run 'pronet-talk' on both the
  server and the client.  This button should only be clicked from the
  client computer.  And the server should have been started up first.

  The chooser gadget selects the unit number to run pronet-talk on,
  the same unit number as the server.

  A window opens up on each computer, into which anything you type
  is repeated on the other computer.

@endnode


@node "bugs" "Bugs"


  Bugs
  ====

  Not a bug as such, but with using AWNPipe to create the gui, the
  loading time of the gui is maybe slower than it could be. Perhaps
  if I come across the E modules for 3.9 I can do away with AWNPipe.


@endnode


